<DOC><DOCNO> AP890930-0125 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-89 2236EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-JetlinerBaby     09-30 0220</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Jetliner Baby,0225</SECOND><HEAD>Pregnancy Delays Jail Term For Mother Who Gave Birth On Plane</HEAD><DATELINE>REDWOOD CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A woman who gave birth in anairplane bathroom and stuffed the infant in a wastebasket won't goto jail until December because she is expecting another baby soon,officials said.   Christina LoCasto of New York City was to begin a six-month jailterm Oct. 14, but a San Mateo County Superior Court judge decidedFriday that her sentence should begin after the birth of her fourthchild, which is due in mid-October.   LoCasto, 25, pleaded no contest in May to a charge of felonychild endangerment in a plea bargain. She could have been sentencedto six years in prison if she had been tried and convicted.   The mother of two other children, LoCasto gave birth in thebathroom of a United Airlines flight between Newark, N.J., and SanFrancisco. The baby was found under the sink shortly after theairplane landed at San Francisco International Airport on July 13,1988.   LoCasto told caseworkers last year she was afraid to tell herhusband about her third pregnancy because they were having maritalproblems.   A juvenile court judge awarded temporary custody of the baby,named Alyssa, to her paternal grandparents. Another hearing on hercustody will be held Oct. 25.</TEXT></DOC>